<br>
1-600 = 60% chance, no return to patron.<br>
601-800 = 20% chance, 40% return (double bet) to patron.<br>
801-1000 = 20% chance, 60% return (tripple bet) to patron.<br>
<br>
So if 1000 randoms were done, and all numbers having an equal chance of showing, 60% of patrons would lose their pp to the house, 20% would take 40% of the houses profits, and 20% would take 60% of the houses profits.  That's 100% in, 100% out.<br>
<br>
That's assuming it was a /random 1 1000.<br>
/random 0 1000 would put the odds _slightly_ in favour of the house. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=59365" target="top">Kathodos</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> - Battle Cleric of Tunare - Tholuxe Paells<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=279732" target="top">Kantreach</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> - Arch Mage Antagonist - Tholuxe Paells</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=darkerplanes>DarkerPlanes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#333333>(12/4/02 7:16:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8044.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: hmm...maybe not</span><hr size=1> uggghhh<br>
<br>
First of all, yes, I was talking about Running the Casino, not playing it....the odds of you winning when playing the Casino are against you...<br>
<br>
Second of all...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Someone said...<br>
You have a 40% chance of winning and a 60% chance of losing on every roll. I can't imagine how people could be so stupid<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, your are absolutely right, people are so stupid.  In the real world, in places like Las Vegas and Atlantic City, and any other gambling establishment there is one constant rule.<br>
<br>
The odds are ALWAYS stacked in favor of the house (with a few notable exceptions).  After all, if the odds weren't the casino would lose money, and casinos would not be a viable business.<br>
<br>
Roulete is probably my favorite example of this.  The game offers a possible bet on numbers 1 to 32, some, all, odds, evens, and red/black.  The pay off for betting on one number is 32x and which means you have a one out of thirty two .  However, the casino fixes the odds by adding another factor to the wheel: 00 or Double Zero.  So that means there are 33 possible outcomes to the spin of the wheel, yet the maximum payout is only 32x instead of 33x as it should be.  Thus, statistically, by fixing the maximum payout under the probility, the casino over time will always win.  <br>
<br>
Slot machines are...obvious..<br>
<br>
Perhaps the only game where the odds are not fixed is blackjack, because there, elements of player skill (card counting, statistical analysis, and psychology) become viable when playing the game.<br>
<br>
So, your right chief, however, as long as people like that exist, there will be a market for this, and a way for an enterprising person to make a quick plat (or buck).<br>
<br>
Dark<br>
52 Elementalist<br>
